Hey!

I was passing in a Batch object into the Stage as I wanted to reduce my draw calls, but I found that if the Stage doesn't own the Batch instance it will still call begin() and end() on it. 

In the draw() method.

```
if (batch != null) {
    batch.setProjectionMatrix(camera.combined);
    batch.begin();
    root.draw(batch, 1);
    batch.end();
}
```

It would be awesome if the Stage instance didn't own the Batch it just assumed that the Batch was ready to render.

```
if (batch != null) {
    if (!ownsBatch) batch.setProjectionMatrix(camera.combined);
    if (!ownsBatch) batch.begin();
    root.draw(batch, 1);
    if (!ownsBatch) batch.end();
}
```

Is this by design or an oversight? I could well be doing something really wrong here and there maybe a better way for me to do this?

I'm playing with Json and the example shown in the documentation works perfectly. [http://hastebin.com/elocacukul.avrasm]

However, if I do not use the setters to set the values first, the method toJson(); will return empty [http://hastebin.com/azovayihem.avrasm]. I'm not sure if this is a feature or bug. I suppose something like this could be considered extraneous as one wouldn't usually need to save the default initialized value. However, if say one were to allow a serialized JSON Setting Class to be exchanged over the net and one then changed the previous version's default values, some of the old settings might still be retained. Perhaps I should be implementing serialVersionUID but I would think the problem in that scenario would still persist.

Someone on IRC mentioned that I might be doing it wrong. If so, I would suggest that the documentation be more clear on the requirements of the Json.Serializable.

I've also tried some reflecting to see if I could find the names of the fields that are initialized during declaration. I've tried the code below with success.

for (Field f: settingTest.getClass().getFields()) {
      try {
        System.out.println(f.getGenericType() + " " + f.getName() + " = " + f.get(settingTest));
      } catch (IllegalAccessException e) {
        e.printStackTrace();
      }
}

Edit: Some further testing shows that JSON will output the correct JSON if the class being parsed is a class within the class calling the toJson(); method. If you are trying to parse a top-level class it will output {}. So, [http://hastebin.com/akuxukeqaq.avrasm] will work.

Created default app using LibGDX version 1.6.0
Compiled with RoboVM 1.5

```
@Override
public void render ()
{
    Gdx.gl.glClearColor(1, 0, 0, 1);
    Gdx.gl.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);

    batch.begin();
    Gdx.gl20.glEnable(GL20.GL_SCISSOR_TEST);
    batch.draw(img, 0, 0);
    Gdx.gl20.glDisable(GL20.GL_SCISSOR_TEST);
    batch.end();
}
```
